A?    Process hazard analysis and review, including corrective action follow-up requirements;

A?    Standard operating procedures that all operators of the refrigeration system must follow;

A?    Formal operator training (80 hours minimum);

A?    Preventative maintenance to ensure that the entire refrigeration system is mechanically sound;

A?    Procedures to ensure that changes to the refrigeration system are managed so ammonia flow remains safe;

A?    Safety review prior to the start-up of new or modified equipment;

A?    Audits of the PSM and RMP programs;

A?    Incident investigations to ensure that lessons are learned to prevent future incidents;

A?    Employee involvement in risk reduction programs;

A?    Contractor safety procedures are reviewed to ensure outside workers exercise the same safety  consciousness as brewery employees;

A?    A work permit system that ensures all welding work is conducted safely.

A?    Process safety information; and 

A?    Emergency planning and response.



The brewery additionally complies with the requirements of the OSHA PSM standard (40 CFR 1910.119), the EPA RMP rules (40 CFR 68), and the ANSI/IIAR 2-1992 standard for Equipment, Design, and Installation of Ammonia Mechanical Refrigerating Systems.



Five-Year Accident History



The brewery has had no releases that have caused onsite or offsite injuries, or damage to property or the environment.  In fact, the brewery has never had releases with these impacts since it began operation in 1970.



